FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, OVINE - CYPRUS (10): POSITIVE SEROLOGY
************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Wed 14 Nov 2007
Source: Associated Press via Pravda [edited]
<http://newsfromrussia.com/print/science/100912-illness_outbreak-0>


Cyprus began slaughtering about 1500 sheep after confirmed
foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] in 2 more farms.

Fotis Fotiou said the EU-accredited lab in Pirbright, England
confirmed the new outbreaks of the highly contagious virus Tuesday
[13 Nov 2007; "new" is probably an inaccurate term; there is no clue
of a spreading disease but rather of additional serological tests;
see in commentary on Cyprus the follow-up report to the OIE, dated 13
Nov 2007. - Mod.AS].

Authorities planned to destroy 1500 animals from one farm in the
livestock breeding area of Dromolaxia and slaughter another 70 from
another farm on Thursday [15 Nov 2007].

"(Farmers) must understand that whatever measures are taken, even
slaughtering animals, they are taken to prevent the worst," Fotiou
said.

Some 560 goats, sheep and pigs have already been slaughtered in the
Dromolaxia area since tests from the Pirbright lab confirmed the
infection at 4 farms on 5 Nov 2007.

EU food safety experts have imposed a ban on livestock, meat and
dairy exports from Cyprus because of the outbreak but made an
exception for the island's famed halloumi cheese [a commendable
delicacy! - Mod.AS].

Cyprus is not a major meat exporter, but halloumi cheese is one of
the country's key farm exports, along with potatoes and citrus fruits.

--
