ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[2]
Date: Wed 14 Nov 2007
Source: Cyprus Mail [edited]
<http://www.cyprus-mail.com/news/main.php?id=35904&cat_id=1>


There is no selective culling; if animals are found to have FMD in a
farm, then all the livestock must go, a senior Veterinary Service
official clarified yesterday [13 Nov 2007].

Pavlos Toumazos cleared up the confusion over the fate of 3500
animals by stating clearly there was no way you could pick and choose
which animals would be culled or not once FMD was found.

The animals belong to 2 farms in the 3-km exclusion zone in
Dromolaxia, with the owners awaiting results of tests undertaken at
the Vet Services Laboratory.

Agriculture Minister Fotis Fotiou had hinted earlier that a wholesale
culling was not a certainty, even if some of the samples came back
positive for FMD. The minister had suggested that subsequent culling
depended on the number of cases and the scale of the disease.

"You cannot have selective culling," clarified Toumazos. "The
specific case where we took certain samples from animals was for
further examinations. We didn't choose to kill 3 animals with the aim
of separating the infected ones and leaving the rest in the farm," he
added.

Asked whether all the animals would be culled if the tests came back
positive, the official replied: "Definitely."

Toumazos noted that initial tests had come back positive from the 2
farms in Dromolaxia. He also highlighted that, so far, the test
results from the laboratory in London matched those of the Vet
Services Lab.

Regarding the rumours and theories floating around regarding the
existence of FMD on the island, he said: "They should let us do our
work and get our results instead of everybody talking and giving
views on where and why, so we can limit the situation to the 3-km
exclusion zone. And as we can see, the results we're getting don't
show the virus anywhere outside of this zone, so we can save
livestock farming."

The Veterinary Services have tightened measures to clamp down on the
potential spread of FMD in Cyprus.

According to yesterday's [13 Nov 2007] announcement, the import and
export of live animals susceptible to the disease (pigs, sheep, goats
and cattle) has been banned. The transportation of animals from one
farm to another throughout Cyprus has been prohibited as well as from
farms to market places for trade. No animals from within the 3-km
exclusion zone may be taken for slaughter. An exception to the rule
is pigs within the zone which, once checked and approved, can be
taken to Kofinou or CYPRA slaughterhouse along with a Vet Services
permit. However, the pigs cannot be put in contact with other animals
from outside the zone brought to the slaughterhouse and must be kept
separate at all times. Slaughter of pigs within the zone can only
take place on certain days, while once slaughtered they must be kept
in separate freezers for a 48-hour period.

Animals outside the zone can be taken for slaughter as long as they
go directly from the farms to the slaughterhouse.

