******
[3]
Date: Wed 14 Nov 2007
Source: ObserverCyprus.com (Northern Cyprus) [edited]
<http://www.observercyprus.com/observer/NewsDetails.aspx?id=2472#>


Following the confirmation of the presence of FMD in animals in
southern Cyprus, Turkish Cypriot Minister of Agriculture Onder
Sennaroglu issued a statement asking citizens to be sensitive about
the precautions that were being taken.

In his statement, Sennaroglu said that a crisis desk had been set up
at the Turkish Cypriot Prime Ministry in order to monitor the effects
of the viral disease discovered on a sheep farm in southern Cyprus.
He stated that 2 professionals from Turkey had been invited to
northern Cyprus to research the issue and reiterated that the disease
had not yet been seen here. The Minister said that the quarantine
area around the infected farm in southern Cyprus had been increased
to 10 km by the Greek Cypriot administration and that the closest
Turkish village is at least 8-10 km distant from the quarantined
area. [See a map of Cyprus showing its division, by a UN buffer zone,
into a Cyprus Government area (Greek Cypriot area) and a northern,
Turkish Cypriot-administered area at
<http://www.mlahanas.de/Cyprus/Image/CyprusMap.png>.
The alleged outbreak, in Dromolaxia, is about 5 km southwest of
Larnaca. - Mod.AS].

Sennaroglu called on all citizens to be sensitive to the prophylactic
measures being taken at south-north crossing points and the ban on
the importation of any number of animals or amount animal products
from southern Cyprus and said: "We ask our citizens to be sensitive
about this issue. The FMD found in cloven hoofed animals is viral and
can pass from one animal to another quite easily."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[This is a complex and confusing situation.

The Cypriot authorities have to abide by EU requirements regarding
FMD, and since it seems that the EU experts have decided that
positive serological tests are indicative of infection and sufficient
for declaring an outbreak, culling has been prescribed.

Cyprus' follow-up report No 1, sent on 13 Nov 2007 to the OIE,
addressed the farm "Dromolaxia 2, Larnaca," specifying that the
outbreak started on 2 Nov 2007 and resolved on 6 Nov 2007; indeed, an
unusually short-lived FMD outbreak. The laboratory results are clear,
and their reliability is not contested: positive 3ABC tests (Cyprus
National lab); positive neutralisation tests (Pirbright); negative
PCR's (Pirbright).

The report further says that: "Lesions were found in the mouth of
lambs in the sheep farm." According to this moderator's experience,
buccal lesions in sheep are not very common, while podal lesions and
subsequent lameness are the rule. Such lesions are not mentioned in
the report. For the full report, see
<http://www.oie.int/wahid-prod/public.php?page=single_report&pop=1&reportid=6470>.

From a reliable source in Cyprus, we have obtained the following
additional data:
1. All animals tested were adults.
2. No clinical symptoms of FMD were observed in all cattle and pig
farms in the Protected zone of 3 km or in the Surveillance zone of 10
km.
3. No FMD antibodies were detected in all blood samples from about
1250 cattle and pigs tested in Cyprus and at Pirbright.
4. Cypriot and visiting Greek experts did not report any FMD
symptoms; "very mild symptoms" were suspected by an European EU
expert (probably, these are the lesions referred to in the follow-up
report).
5. No FMD vaccination is officially known to have been applied in
both parts of Cyprus in recent years; however, the possibility that
FMD vaccines have been imported could not be excluded.
6. Clinical and serological evidence for the presence of bluetongue,
in sheep and cattle, have been reported.

The above information is supportive of our earlier observation,
namely that the whole described event may have resulted from the
application of (inactivated) FMD vaccine (See 20071109.3637), which
has given rise to the neutralising antibodies. The positive 3ABC
tests, detecting Non Specific Proteins (NSP), may be indicative of a
past application of (partly or poorly purified) inactivated FMD
vaccines. Whether such vaccines have indeed been injected into the
(adult) tested sheep, and -- in case affirmative -- when and where
this could have happened, deserves a thorough investigation. The view
of Pirbright's experts on the issue would be valuable.

It is also worth a reminder that the 1st examined case, in a sheep,
was initially suspected to be bluetongue. The serological test
performed was found to be negative; this could probably be explained
by sampling carried out before seroconversion. The prescribed test
for a clinically suspected BT case is virus detection, either by its
isolation (preferably by i.v. inoculation into embryonated chicken
eggs) or by PCR.

Official information on tests for bluetongue in Cyprus during 2007
will be helpful. - Mod.AS]
